TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Organizational Taxonomy: Definition and Design
AU  - Rich, Philip
Y1  - 1992/10/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1992.4279068
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1992.4279068
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 758
EP  - 781
VL  - 17
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Organizational typologies provide an effective data storage and retrieval system, as well as a means for theory development. However, existing typologies are typically limited, failing to meet broad standards. This article discusses contemporary organizational classification in the context of empirical, theoretical, and evolutionary perspectives. Consideration is given to the theoretical and numerical basis for grouping organizations, and an overview is provided of the conceptual and operational development of hierarchical taxonomies and the selection of organizational variables.
AB  - Organizational typologies provide an effective data storage and retrieval system, as well as a means for theory development. However, existing typologies are typically limited, failing to meet broad standards. This article discusses contemporary organizational classification in the context of empirical, theoretical, and evolutionary perspectives. Consideration is given to the theoretical and numerical basis for grouping organizations, and an overview is provided of the conceptual and operational development of hierarchical taxonomies and the selection of organizational variables.
